Great Leader's Rebirth
London — — The Battle of Waterloo has been over for two hundred years, Napoleon's disastrous failure in that battle severely damaged France's self-esteem, to the point that General Charles de Gaulle did not mention it when writing the history of the French military.
Despite this, if you acknowledge that "great" is a personal quality of sorts, then Napoleon and de Gaulle are both the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there fundamentally does not exist such a thing as a "great leader".
In Marx's view, France's class struggle created an environment where "strange incompetent" figures like Napoleon could become heroes.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon cannot be considered a particularly outstanding general, his victories should be attributed to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
No matter whether Napoleon is great or not, we need to clarify whether greatness can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important standards.
First, can this leader accurately recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, and so did his fellow German Conrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's unforgettable words, both heard "the rustling of the Almighty's cloak".
Secondly, did this leader make any important decisions?
Naturally, if a leader is forced to make a decision, neither can such be criticized, nor can it be praised.
Therefore, the key lies in whether a leader has the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons, and make the correct decision for the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore be listed in any great leader's rankings.
He almost single-handedly pulled France out of the post-war downgrading.
After regaining power in 1958, he saved his country again, suppressed two failed coups, ended the Algerian War, and established the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, Charles de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their position in the post-war global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill establishing their own worldviews was somewhat too large.
Their successors looked at the world - and the role of their own country - for many years in a way of discussing and distorting rationality and decision-making.
It was a result that the leaders of the two countries would never be able to achieve again, something comparable to the two great leaders.
But there is one British prime minister who can be compared to her: Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, with as many people liking her as hating her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to the opposition activities of her own cabinet and party members.
You don't need to win the hearts of everyone to be a great leader.
Actually, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her influence.
Except for being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom, she was almost the first female prime minister in other countries in the world, and Thatcher helped turn around the UK's economic downturn.
Not to mention, her attack on overly powerful labor unions made it more manageable at a time when the country seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be a candidate for the "great leader".
Similarly, although far from being flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China also has the qualifications to be a great leader.
In addition to assisting Mao Zedong in doing evil, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square Massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China onto a path of unprecedented development and prosperity that would ultimately allow billions of Chinese to escape poverty.
Many people think that Singapore's founder and long-time prime minister Lee Kuan Yew was extremely great, although he might have hoped to make a name for himself on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of the country does not seem to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I said that Luxembourg, being a small country, was unlikely to produce great leaders, and I did not have any intention to offend, especially given the relatively low level of political controversy in the country.
The United States is vast enough to be a cradle for the birth of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — — although not exactly intellectual giants — — nevertheless showed exceptional judgment in establishing the post-war international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possess exceptional gifts — — namely, the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was well-rounded.
He accomplished a great task: resolving the Cuban missile crisis.
He is gifted beyond comparison; in fact, after his death, his assassination solidified the legacy he left behind.
In South Africa, no one is considered a great figure after President Mandela's death; Mandela embodied courage, authority, and majestic generosity.
In fact, he was the most charming and captivating leader I had ever seen; the other two -- former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell -- were either not African or of African-American descent.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to call themselves great is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning, but rarely made mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin when he invaded Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on the migrant crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders —— the exercisers of political power —— can change the situation, whether it becomes better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, and she has pointed the way for Europe to cope with high-level survival crises.
